<br>
So, I still don't much care for the anti-melee sentiment that I read lately.  It does remind me of caster-envy from back when but that's neither here nor there.<br>
<br>
Many say that a Rogue (or other melee character) does way too much damage in a raid.  In reality, a Rogue that has the support of a Tank, an Enchanter, buffers, a healer and preferably a Bard will; provided they have also kept up their equipment, skills and AA abilities, produce a great deal of damage in a situation where the target is not highly melee resistant, has an ass that can be stabbed and doesn't disable melee through AE, knockbacks, damage shield or other means.  (heehee, I refuse to fix that sentence...)  They don't do this all on their own, nor does anyone on a raid.  Rogues need rides everywhere, they need support in terms of healing, buffing and a solid tank who can hold aggro.  <br>
<br>
Despite what some here like to maintain, we also don't solo worth a frickin' damn and rely on groups to even get to the point where we become effective.  Yes we may get into groups (that have a tank, a healer and CC already) more easily than a Wizard or Mage.  I won't debate that.  Still, do keep in mind that this is our only option for experience gain.  I have spent many a night /lfg for hours only to log out and not play at all.<br>
<br>
Other melee characters have their own issues.  Ask that Warrior next time just how he got to OS before he went /lfg.  It isn't always as simple a life as you see on the raids.  What about the fellow who isn't one of the Main Tanks of the guild, he often feels a little put out.  The Monk who doesn't get on the pull team much likely feels the same.  <br>
<br>
Pah, enough already, I'm not here to make converts.  I guess what I'm getting at is that to simply say that class A does too much damage is missleading in two ways.  First off, a character in a raid is supported by everyone on that raid and the damage that 'that one character' is doing should rightly be attributed to every porter, CoH Mage, healer, buffer, tank, strategist, organizer, puller and scout on that raid.  Secondly, when a class is pared down to damage and little else, it is not too much to expect that they *should* do a good bit of damage in most situations.  <br>
<br>
Yes, casters need balancing in a number of areas.  I'm all for finger-wigglers being able to contribute more damage (or more damage directly as opposed to indirectly as they often do now) to both experience groups and raids.  Still, I don't think this focus item plan was a good way to go about it.<br>
<br>
